ver sharing the gospel and trusting the Spirit.\n</code></pre>",
        "slide_deck_sidecar": "## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"1\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:1 — Strategic Proclamation, Supernatural Results\nThis single verse encapsulates the apostolic missionary pattern: a strategic starting point (the synagogue), a Spirit-empowered method (\"spoke in such a way\"), and a supernatural result (a large, unified church of Jews and Gentiles).\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n",
        "slide_deck_sidecar_html": "<h2>Slide Deck Sidecar</h2>\n<h2>```markdown</h2>\n<p>book: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"1\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre</p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Acts 14:1 — Strategic Proclamation, Supernatural Results</h1>\n<p>This single verse encapsulates the apostolic missionary pattern: a strategic starting point (the synagogue), a Spirit-empowered method (\"spoke in such a way\"), and a supernatural result (a large, unified church of Jews and Gentiles).</p>\n<p><em>Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.</em></p>",
        "cover_art_prompts": "## Cover Art Prompts\n\n```nano-banana-1\nAnchor: V1 lines 1-2 — \"They shook the dust from off their feet / And walked another city street\"\nSepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. Cinematic still of the backs of two men in simple, travel-worn 1st-century robes, walking with purpose down a dusty, sun-drenched stone street of an ancient Anatolian city. The sun is low, casting long shadows before them. Shot on 35mm film, anamorphic lens, shallow depth of field, creating a sense of resilient forward motion.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures.\n```\n```nano-banana-2\nAnchor: Chorus lines 3-4 — \"A crowd of Jew and Greek to see / The one new man they came to be\"\nSepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. Interior of an ancient synagogue, light streaming through a high window. A diverse crowd of 1st-century Jews (with prayer shawls) and Greeks (in simple tunics) are gathered, their faces a mix of awe and understanding, looking towards an unseen speaker. The light illuminates the dust motes in the air, creating a sacred atmosphere. Photorealistic, volumetric light.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures.\n```\n```nano-banana-3\nAnchor: V2 lines 1-2 — \"They read the scrolls of what was old / The story that the prophets told\"\nSepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. A close-up cinematic still focusing on a pair of weathered hands unrolling an ancient Hebrew scroll on a wooden lectern inside a stone synagogue. The focus is sharp on the Hebrew text, with the background softly blurred, showing the listening crowd. Natural light from a side window highlights the texture of the parchment and the hands.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures.\n```\n```nano-banana-4\nAnchor: Bridge lines 1-2 — \"Your Spirit gives the power / For this appointed hour\"\nSepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. An abstract and symbolic image. A simple, empty wooden lectern in a synagogue is bathed in a powerful, almost tangible shaft of golden light from above. The air seems to shimmer with energy. The focus is on the light itself as the source of power, not on any person. The mood is one of divine presence and empowerment.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures.\n```\n```nano-banana-5\nAnchor: Outro lines 2-3 — \"Let us now speak Your Name\"\nSepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. A modern scene echoing the ancient one. A diverse group of people (different ages and ethnicities) in a simple, contemporary church setting, their mouths open as if singing or speaking with conviction. The shot is framed from a low angle, looking up, conveying a sense of unity and bold proclamation. Warm, inviting light.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures.\n```\n```nano-banana-title\nAnchor: Song Title — \"The Way They Spoke\"\nSepia parchment, dust-light, ochre palette. A powerful, central image for the song. Two silhouetted figures stand before a large, diverse crowd inside a 1st-century synagogue. A single, brilliant beam of light comes from above and behind them, illuminating the crowd and casting the speakers' long shadows forward. The entire focus is on the effect of their unseen words. Cinematic still, shot on 35mm film, high contrast.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures.\n```\n```nano-banana-horizon\nAnchor: Christo-telic Horizon — The great, diverse multitude before the throne (Rev 7:9)\nA vast, uncountable multitude of people from every conceivable nation, tribe, and tongue, dressed in white robes. They stand before a brilliant, unseen throne, their faces filled with adoration. The lighting is ethereal and golden, suggesting a heavenly reality. This is the ultimate fulfillment of the small gathering in the Iconium synagogue. Symbolic, not literal depiction of heaven.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures.\n```\n",
