 lives</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>τῶν</td>\n<td>tōn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-GPN</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>ἐθνῶν</td>\n<td>ethnōn</td>\n<td>G1484</td>\n<td>ἔθνος</td>\n<td>N-GPN</td>\n<td>Gentiles / nations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>κατὰ</td>\n<td>kata</td>\n<td>G2596</td>\n<td>κατά</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>against (+gen)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>τῶν</td>\n<td>tōn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-GPM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>ἀδελφῶν</td>\n<td>adelphōn</td>\n<td>G80</td>\n<td>ἀδελφός</td>\n<td>N-GPM</td>\n<td>brothers</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong>\nBut the disbelieving Jews stirred up and poisoned the souls of the Gentiles against the brothers.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong>\nBut the Jews who refused to believe stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds against the believers.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong>\nBut the Jews who willfully disobeyed [the gospel message] incited the Gentiles and maliciously corrupted their inner disposition [lit. their souls], turning them against the brothers [in Christ].</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** Unbelief is never neutral; it is an active, hostile force that often recruits others by poisoning their minds against the truth and its messengers.\n\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):**\n    *   *Individual:* The sinful heart's reflex is not just to reject God but to resent those who represent Him, leading to slander and malicious efforts to turn others against them.\n    *   *Corporate:* Communities and cultures can be \"poisoned\" by lies, making them hostile environments for the gospel and for God's people.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Jesus Christ, the ultimate \"Brother,\" faced the ultimate hostility and slander, yet He did not revile in return (1 Pet 2:23). On the cross, He absorbed the full poison of human sin and defeated the very power that animates such opposition (Col 2:15). Because He was victorious, those who are \"in Him\" are secure, even when minds are poisoned against them. His victory, not our popularity, is our foundation.\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Do not be surprised by hostility, slander, or misrepresentation. Expect it as a normal part of the Christian life (1 Pet 4:12). Cultivate a heart that entrusts itself to a faithful Creator, just as Jesus did (1 Pet 4:19).\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When opposed, respond with blessing, not retaliation (Matt 5:44; Rom 12:14). Focus on speaking the truth in love (Eph 4:15), recognizing that the real battle is for the souls of those being deceived.\n    *   *Relational:* Strengthen the fellowship of \"the brothers.\" When one part of the body is slandered, the whole body suffers and must rally together in prayer and support (1 Cor 12:26).\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your workplace or community, be aware that opposition to Christian ethics or truth may not be based on reason, but on a pre-existing, poisoned disposition. Your task is not to win an argument, but to live a life of such integrity that it exposes the lies (1 Pet 2:12).\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** We praise You, O Sovereign Lord, that even the malicious plots of men cannot thwart Your purpose. You are the defender of Your people, the One whose truth prevails over every lie, and whose kingdom advances not in spite of opposition, but through it.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> Unbelief is never neutral; it is an active, hostile force that often recruits others by poisoning their minds against the truth and its messengers.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Individual:</em> The sinful heart's reflex is not just to reject God but to resent those who represent Him, leading to slander and malicious efforts to turn others against them.</li>\n<li><em>Corporate:</em> Communities and cultures can be \"poisoned\" by lies, making them hostile environments for the gospel and for God's people.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Jesus Christ, the ultimate \"Brother,\" faced the ultimate hostility and slander, yet He did not revile in return (1 Pet 2:23). On the cross, He absorbed the full poison of human sin and defeated the very power that animates such opposition (Col 2:15). Because He was victorious, those who are \"in Him\" are secure, even when minds are poisoned against them. His victory, not our popularity, is our foundation.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Do not be surprised by hostility, slander, or misrepresentation. Expect it as a normal part of the Christian life (1 Pet 4:12). Cultivate a heart that entrusts itself to a faithful Creator, just as Jesus did (1 Pet 4:19).</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> When opposed, respond with blessing, not retaliation (Matt 5:44; Rom 12:14). Focus on speaking the truth in love (Eph 4:15), recognizing that the real battle is for the souls of those being deceived.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Strengthen the fellowship of \"the brothers.\" When one part of the body is slandered, the whole body suffers and must rally together in prayer and support (1 Cor 12:26).</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your workplace or community, be aware that opposition to Christian ethics or truth may not be based on reason, but on a pre-existing, poisoned disposition. Your task is not to win an argument, but to live a life of such integrity that it exposes the lies (1 Pet 2:12).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> We praise You, O Sovereign Lord, that even the malicious plots of men cannot thwart Your purpose. You are the defender of Your people, the One whose truth prevails over every lie, and whose kingdom advances not in spite of opposition, but through it.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:2 — \"...stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds against the brothers.\"\nKEY TERM:     ἐκάκωσαν (*ekakōsan*, \"they poisoned / embittered\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Opposition to the gospel actively poisons minds against God's people.\nIMAGE:        A whisper in the ear, turning a friend into a foe.\nAPPLICATION:  For myself: Expect slander; entrust my reputation to God, not my own defense.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to the God whose truth cannot be poisoned and whose church cannot be stopped.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:2 — &quot;...stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds against the brothers.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>ἐκάκωσαν (*ekakōsan*, &quot;they poisoned / embittered&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Opposition to the gospel actively poisons minds against God&#x27;s people.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A whisper in the ear, turning a friend into a foe.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For myself: Expect slander; entrust my reputation to God, not my own defense.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to the God whose truth cannot be poisoned and whose church cannot be stopped.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt like someone’s mind was turned against you before you even had a chance to speak? That’s the exact tactic described in Acts 14:2. After a powerful and successful time of ministry in the city of Iconium, where many Jews and Gentiles believed the gospel, a sharp opposition arose. The Bible is brutally honest about the source: \"the Jews who refused to believe.\" Their unbelief wasn't passive. Luke uses two powerful verbs: they \"stirred up\" the non-believing Gentiles and \"poisoned\" their minds—literally, their souls—against the Christian believers.\n\nThis wasn't a theological debate; it was spiritual warfare fought with slander and suspicion. It reminds us that opposition to our faith is rarely neutral or purely intellectual. It is often an active, malicious attempt to corrupt someone's perception of Christ and His people. But the gospel's power is not nullified by this. Our hope isn't in winning everyone over, but in the victory Christ has already won over the father of lies (John 16:33). This week, if you face misunderstanding or hostility for your faith, remember that you are walking a well-worn path. Instead of fighting back with the world's weapons, entrust yourself to the God who is faithful and just, and let your good conduct be your ultimate defense (1 Peter 2:12).\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt like someone’s mind was turned against you before you even had a chance to speak? That’s the exact tactic described in Acts 14:2. After a powerful and successful time of ministry in the city of Iconium, where many Jews and Gentiles believed the gospel, a sharp opposition arose. The Bible is brutally honest about the source: \"the Jews who refused to believe.\" Their unbelief wasn't passive. Luke uses two powerful verbs: they \"stirred up\" the non-believing Gentiles and \"poisoned\" their minds—literally, their souls—against the Christian believers.</p>\n<p>This wasn't a theological debate; it was spiritual warfare fought with slander and suspicion. It reminds us that opposition to our faith is rarely neutral or purely intellectual. It is often an active, malicious attempt to corrupt someone's perception of Christ and His people. But the gospel's power is not nullified by this. Our hope isn't in winning everyone over, but in the victory Christ has already won over the father of lies (John 16:33). This week, if you face misunderstanding or hostility for your faith, remember that you are walking a well-worn path. Instead of fighting back with the world's weapons, entrust yourself to the God who is faithful and just, and let your good conduct be your ultimate defense (1 Peter 2:12).</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What two specific actions did the unbelieving Jews take against the believers in Acts 14:2?\n    A: They \"stirred up\" the Gentiles and \"poisoned\" their minds against them.\n2.  What part of the Gentiles did the opponents target, according to the Greek text?\n    A: Their ψυχὰς (*psychas*), meaning their souls, minds, or inner lives.\n3.  What does this verse teach us about the nature of sin and unbelief?\n    A: It teaches that unbelief is not passive disagreement but an active, hostile spiritual condition that seeks to recruit others and maliciously suppress the truth of the gospel.\n4.  Based on this passage, what should a believer expect and how should they prepare?\n    A: I should expect that my faith may provoke active opposition and slander, and I can prepare by grounding my security in Christ's victory, not in human approval.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What two specific actions did the unbelieving Jews take against the believers in Acts 14:2?\n    A: They \"stirred up\" the Gentiles and \"poisoned\" their minds against them.</li>\n<li>What part of the Gentiles did the opponents target, according to the Greek text?\n    A: Their ψυχὰς (<em>psychas</em>), meaning their souls, minds, or inner lives.</li>\n<li>What does this verse teach us about the nature of sin and unbelief?\n    A: It teaches that unbelief is not passive disagreement but an active, hostile spiritual condition that seeks to recruit others and maliciously suppress the truth of the gospel.</li>\n<li>Based on this passage, what should a believer expect and how should they prepare?\n    A: I should expect that my faith may provoke active opposition and slander, and I can prepare by grounding my security in Christ's victory, not in human approval.</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The gospel overcomes all opposition.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The pivot from success to persecution.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Historical narrative of spiritual warfare.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: The normative pattern of the Church Age mission.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: The ongoing enmity of Gen 3:15.\n\nGate 1: PASS — Justification is rooted in the three key verbs of Acts 14:2.\nGate 2: PASS — Every nugget from the exegesis is mapped.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is confident expectation in God's sovereignty over opposition.\nGate 4: PASS — Metaphors of poison, dust, and warfare are from the text and its context.\nGate 5: PASS — The synthesis of spiritual warfare (Christian), internal conflict (Jewish), and slander (Midrashic pattern) is present.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully unpacked.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past success), V2 (present reality), Bridge (POV pivot to \"we\").\nGate 8: PASS — The Bridge is the reveal, shifting the focus to God's power.\nGate 9: PASS — Weight falls on key words like \"stirred,\" \"poisoned,\" \"stand.\"\nGate 10: PASS — Plosives and fricatives in the Chorus (\"distrust,\" \"just\") contrast with liquids in the Bridge (\"will,\" \"still\").\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds move from the closed sounds of conspiracy to the open sounds of praise.\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables, well within Miller's Law.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct with two blank lines between blocks.\nGate 14: PASS — The final word \"stand\" ends with a firm consonant blend.\nGate 15: PASS — The Chorus is a clear, memorable headline of the verse's meaning.\nGate 16: PASS — Both verses maintain a consistent iambic/anapestic rhythm.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep theological concepts (spiritual warfare, slander) are compressed into simple lyrics.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses are the bait (story/application), Chorus is the barb (scriptural truth).\nGate 19: PASS — The Bridg